FAQs
Is it expensive to study in Lithuania?

Tuition fees in Lithuania vary depending on the university and program. On average, tuition fees for international students range from 1,500 to 5,000 euros per year for bachelor's programs and from 2,000 to 6,000 euros per year for master's programs. Living costs are also relatively affordable, with an average monthly expense of around 400 to 700 euros for accommodation, food, transportation, and other expenses.
Do I need to speak Lithuanian to study in Lithuania?

While some programs in Lithuania are taught in Lithuanian, many universities offer programs taught in English, especially at the master's level. If you choose to study in a program taught in Lithuanian, you may be required to demonstrate proficiency in the language. However, for programs taught in English, proficiency in Lithuanian is not required.
Are there scholarship opportunities for international students in Lithuania?

Yes, there are scholarship opportunities for international students to study in Lithuania. The Lithuanian government offers scholarships through the State Scholarship Program, which covers full tuition fees and provides a monthly stipend for living expenses. Additionally, many Lithuanian universities offer scholarships based on academic merit, financial need, or other criteria. It's advisable to check with your chosen university or the Lithuanian Ministry of Education and Science for specific scholarship opportunities.
Can I work while study in Lithuania?

Yes, international students in Lithuania are allowed to work part-time while studying. Students from EU/EEA countries do not need a work permit to work in Lithuania, while students from non-EU/EEA countries are permitted to work up to 20 hours per week during the academic year and full-time during holidays. However, it's important to note that income from part-time work may not be sufficient to cover all expenses, so it's advisable to have additional financial support.
